│ fcmp ninf olt float %x, 0.0` with `%x = -inf` evaluates to `poison`. The `ninf` flag on    │
│ `fcmp` instructions causes them to return `poison` if one operand is infinity and the      │
│ other is not.\n    *   `%cmp2 = fcmp ogt float %x, -0.0` with `%x = -inf` evaluates to     │
│ `false`.\n    *   `%cond = select i1 %cmp2, i1 %cmp1, i1 false` becomes `select i1 false,  │
│ i1 poison, i1 false`, which results in `false`. The `poison` value is in the untaken       │
│ branch of the `select`, so it is not propagated.\n*   **Target IR**:\n    *   `%1 = call   │
│ ninf float @llvm.fabs.f32(float -inf)` results in `+inf`.\n    *   `%cond = fcmp ninf olt  │
│ float %1, 0.0` becomes `fcmp ninf olt float +inf, 0.0`, which evaluates to                 │
│ `poison`.\n\nThe source returns a concrete value (`false`), while the target returns       │
│ `poison`. This makes the target more poisonous than the source, which is a                 │
