│ This is an interesting bug in `InstCombine`. The core issue is an incorrect transformation │
│ of a floating-point range check into an `fabs`-based comparison, which is unsound when     │
│ `ninf` (no signed infinity) fast-math flag is present and the comparison is against zero.  │
│                                                                                            │
│ The original code is logically equivalent to `(%x > -0.0) && (%x < 0.0)`. With `ninf`, if  │
│ `%x` is `-infinity`, the expression evaluates to `false`. The transformed code, `fabs(%x)  │
│ < 0.0`, evaluates to `poison` for the same input, making the transformation incorrect.     │
│                                                                                            │
│ The bug lies in `foldLogicOfFCmps` in `InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp`. This function attempts to │
│ optimize range checks. The specific logic for this transformation is:                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // Canonicalize the range check idiom:                                                     │
│ // and (fcmp olt/ole/ult/ule x, C), (fcmp ogt/oge/ugt/uge x, -C)                           │
│ // --> fabs(x) olt/ole/ult/ule C                                                           │
│ // or  (fcmp ogt/oge/ugt/uge x, C), (fcmp olt/ole/ult/ule x, -C)                           │
│ // --> fabs(x) ogt/oge/ugt/uge C                                                           │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ My fix introduces a check to prevent this transformation under the problematic conditions: │
│ specifically, when it's a logical `and`, the comparison constant `C` is zero, and the      │
│ `no-infs` fast-math flag is not set. This ensures that the unsound transformation is not   │
│ performed, fixing the bug while leaving correct optimizations intact.                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ Here is the patch:                                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```patch                                                                                   │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp                              │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp                              │
│ @@ -1531,13 +1531,22 @@                                                                    │
│        std::swap(PredL, PredR);                                                            │
│      }                                                                                     │
│      if (IsLessThanOrLessEqual(IsAnd ? PredL : PredR)) {                                   │
│ +      FastMathFlags FMF = LHS->getFastMathFlags() | RHS->getFastMathFlags();              │
│ +      // This transform is unsafe if C is 0 and we don't have no-infs. The                │
│ +      // logic is: (X > -0.0) && (X < +0.0). For X = -inf, this is false.                 │
│ +      // The transformed logic is: fabs(X) < +0.0. For X = -inf, this is                  │
│ +      // fabs(-inf) < +0.0 => +inf < +0.0, which is poison if ninf is present.            │
│ +      if (IsAnd && LHSC->isZero() && !FMF.noInfs())                                       │
│ +        return nullptr;                                                                   │
│ +                                                                                          │
│        BuilderTy::FastMathFlagGuard Guard(Builder);                                        │
│ -      Builder.setFastMathFlags(LHS->getFastMathFlags() |                                  │
│ -                               RHS->getFastMathFlags());                                  │
│ +      Builder.setFastMathFlags(FMF);                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│        Value *FAbs = Builder.CreateUnaryIntrinsic(Intrinsic::fabs, LHS0);                  │
│        return Builder.CreateFCmp(PredL, FAbs,                                              │
│                                  ConstantFP::get(LHS0->getType(), *LHSC));                 │
│      }                                                                                     │
│    }                                                                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│    return nullptr;                                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
